AGI - The United States has openly criticized Israel for the use of American weapons > in ways incompatible with international humanitarian law during the war in Gaza. After the Israeli forces intensified operations around the southern city of Rafah, where more than a million displaced persons took refuge, the main international ally of the Jewish State admitted in a report published yesterday by the State Department which is "reasonable esteem" that US weapons were used in violation outside the permissible >, although it is not possible to reach "conclusive results" and for this reason did not block the military dispatch.
The U.S. has warned that the damage to the reputation Israel will suffer if it assaults Rafah will far exceed any possible military gain. UN Secretary-General Antonio Guterres reiterated that Gaza risks an "epic humanitarian disaster" > if Israel launched a large-scale land operation in Rafah, while France urged to cease its operations "without delay".
<div </div
&nbsp;
The Israeli premier repeatedly stated that Israel cannot defeat Hamas > and eliminate any possibility that the militant group repeats its bloody attack on October 7 without sending land troops to Rafah in search of the remaining Hamas fighters and Thursday Netanyahu > has even assumed a tone of challenge: "If we have to stay alone, we will do it alone." On Friday, the White House renewed its opposition, but said it had not yet seen any major operation against the city. "Obviously we look with concern but what we have seen in the last 24 hours uncontacted or indicates a wide, large or important ground operation," said the national Security Council spokesman John Kirby.
Earlier this week, Israeli land troops occupied the eastern areas of the city, including the Palestinian side of the border crossing of Rafah between Egypt and Gaza, but have not yet entered the main built area. Israeli military operations around Rafah have already had a serious impact on Gaza civilians,» UN agencies say. More than 100,000 people, many of whom already displaced from other areas of Gaza, fled Rafah this week.
Many have returned to the city of Khan Yunis, where at the beginning of this year they have raged intense fighting, or are piled in shelters along the coast in the central city of Deir al-Balah. The Rafah Pass, which Israeli troops closed on Tuesday, is the only normally used for fuel delivery, and the United Nations said that the resulting exhaustion of stocks within Gaza has effectively blocked operations of humanitarian agencies. The Cogat, the Israeli Ministry of Defense body responsible for Palestinian civil affairs, declared that it delivered 200,000 litres of fuel to Gaza on Friday using another vessel.
